The males of the three species in the “ labyrinthicus ” group (
) differ in the shape of their sternite VIII and in the components of the genitalia. Abantiades rubrus sp. nov. and A. mcquillani are most similar and both species have significantly smaller pseudoteguminal lobes than A. labyrinthicus (see
,
,
). The disto-posterior margin in A. rubrus sp. nov. is straight producing a pseudoteguminal lobe that is triangular with a triangular disto-posterior process. In A. mcquillani the disto-posterior process has a deep concavity distally that produces a distinct posterior facing projection that, with a flat topped pseudoteguminal lobe produces a keel shaped process. In A. rubrus sp. nov. the anterior margin of the saccus is flatter and hence more “U” shaped and the posterior margin of the forward face has a wider deeper notch than in A. mcquillani .
Compared to the above two species A. labyrinthicus (
) is significantly different having a much more massive and longer pseudoteguminal lobe, with a curved and backward raked disto-posterior process. The valva have much thinner distal half, and the twin processes are much longer with inward curved distal portions. The anterior margin of the saccus is more “V” shaped and the vincular arms are markedly different being relatively shorter and thicker and of a different form whereas in the other two species the saccus is less “V” and more “U” shaped and the vincular arms relatively longer and thinner. Sternite VIII (
) is distinctly different having the most complex shape, with lateral margins that are concave but with posterior angled processes absent in the other species.

